file=Cybersecurity/cortex/operational/tool/cortex-tool-requirements.md · c—t:cortex — Tool Requirements=**Specifies needs; does not grant them.** Access configured at deployment (Fleet Charter Rails 1–2). Every external call plan-locked + sandboxed.\n · tb=\| Skill \| Needs \| Why \| · tb=\|---\|---\|---\| · tb=\| detection-engineering \| SIEM read access (Elastic/Splunk API); file read/write \| Fetch alerts, manage rules, document tuning \| · tb=\| security-monitoring \| SIEM read access; case management (if available); file read/write \| Triage queue, case tracking \| · tb=\| security-incident-response \| File read/write; evidence storage (file system); forensics tool access if available \| IR documentation, evidence preservation \| · tb=\| threat-hunting \| Log source read access (endpoint, network, cloud); hunting tool CLIs (if available) \| Data queries, tool execution \| · en/:Explicit non-needs / hard prohibition (the security-inversion)=- **NO execute access to containment tools** (firewall, EDR isolate, IAM suspend, cloud block). cortex recommends containment; the operator executes.\n- **NO write access to production systems or security controls.** cortex writes case files and investigative notes only.\n- **No SIEM write access** for rule changes — detection rules are modified through the operator or change management gate.\n · n:=- cortex is the detection and response brain; it has read access to everything and write access to almost nothing.\n- SIEM read access is the single most important technical dependency — without it, operations are manual.\n